# IoT-Based EV Charging Station Monitoring and Control System

An intelligent IoT solution designed to safely monitor, analyze, and control Electric Vehicle (EV) charging sessions in real-time. This system tracks electrical parameters like current and power, provides overcurrent protection, and uploads live data to a cloud platform for remote access.

---

## 1. Abstract
The rapid adoption of Electric Vehicles (EVs) creates a strong demand for smart, safe, and efficient charging infrastructure. This project presents an IoT-based EV Charge Monitoring System designed to track electrical parameters during a charging session in real-time. By utilizing an ESP32 microcontroller and a high-precision current sensor, the system monitors live current drawing and estimates total power consumption. A cloud-connected IoT dashboard allows users to monitor their vehicle's charging status remotely. Additionally, the system features an automated safety mechanism using a relay module to immediately cut off the power supply during overcurrent or short-circuit faults, protecting both the vehicle battery and the electrical grid.

---

## 2. Introduction
Electric vehicles rely heavily on the health and efficiency of their battery packs. Monitoring the power delivery during a charging cycle is essential to prevent degradation, overheating, and electrical accidents. Manual monitoring is inefficient and cannot offer immediate protection against sudden electrical surges.

This project solves these issues by introducing an automation layer using Internet of Things (IoT) technology. The system continually samples analog signals from electrical sensors, converts them into digital values, calculates power metrics, and pushes the data to a cloud network. This ensures complete transparency, allows cost calculation based on energy units consumed, and provides automated grid-to-vehicle safety isolation.

---

## 3. System Architecture
The system functions through three distinct layers: Data Acquisition (Sensors), Processing & Control (Microcontroller), and Visualization (Cloud Application).

* **Power Source (Grid Input):** Supplies 230V AC power to the EV charger.
* **Relay Protection Circuit:** Placed inline with the active mains wire to act as an automated circuit breaker.
* **Sensing Node:** The ACS712 sensor sits in series with the load to read real-time current changes.
* **Core Processing Unit (ESP32):** Reads analog inputs from sensors, processes mathematical calibrations, executes safety logic, and connects to the internet via its onboard Wi-Fi chip.
* **IoT Cloud Layer:** Receives the processed parameters via MQTT or HTTP protocols and hosts the user-facing visual gauges.

---

## 4. Hardware System Design & Components

| Component Name | Purpose |
| :--- | :--- |
| **ESP32 NodeMCU** | Main microcontroller with built-in Wi-Fi to process data and connect to the cloud. It features a fast clock speed of 240MHz and dual-core processing to handle sensor reading and data transmission simultaneously. |
| **ACS712 Current Sensor (30A)** | Measures the AC/DC current passing into the vehicle's battery. It works on the principle of the Hall-Effect, outputting a linear voltage proportional to the target current. |
| **5V Single-Channel Relay Module** | Acts as an electronic switch to safely connect or disconnect the charger. If the ESP32 detects an overload, it pulls this relay pin LOW to isolate the load. |
| **Jumper Wires & Breadboard** | Used for making prototype circuit connections safely without soldering. |

